It's so cool you still have that doll! All my childhood toys were lost when I was a teenager. We had a small-ish apartment so my parents stored the toys I was no longer playing with in the attic of a house they were building (and given the economy and our complicated financials at the time, it was a very slow process). Then another opportunity presented itself - dad's colleague was selling a larger house closer to the city center, and our family could just about afford it if we sold almost everything we had. So the apartment and the other house were sold. Sadly, we forgot to clear out the attic before the new owner took possession - and when we realized the mistake, he refused to give us the boxes of toys. I still miss my favorite plushie, a fox I can remember getting as a gift when I was four or so. I suppose it would just be gathering dust somewhere now, anyway, but it would be nice to still have it...

@sotto voce 

It was the 1990s, Poland's meanest decade. The Soviet-aligned regime pre-1989 gutted our culture and economy, and the sudden transition to early-stage capitalism in 1989/1990 in a way made things even worse: people accustomed to the scarcity of everything (pre-1989 shops usually had very little in stock, and people queued for hours for whatever there was little of) now became obsessed with money and acquiring wealth. Nobody wanted to let go of anything they laid their hands on. So I blame the 90s rather than that guy as such for the loss of my toys.

We've come a long way from those days, thankfully, even though it's only been 30 years.

